learning¶

  • def of learning: a computer program is said to learn from experience $E$ if its performance at tasks T measured by P improves with experience E

  • E: a set of data

  • T: hard code in algo

  • P: a loss function, optimized w.r.t training data or data we know answer

NN is highly parameterized model¶

  • (artificial) neural networks (ANN, NN) is parametric regression model (collections of individual neurons/nodes that multiple input by weights and add biases) with a ristricted type of non-linearity

  • NN are highly parameterized, so it's very flexible and can approximate any continuous functions given enough size

  • the more number of params, the more fitness of model

  • creative design of architecture, objective function, optimization algorithms and regularization, data augmentation admits many practical applications across domains

why go deep?¶

the deeper the NN

  • higher complexity of learned function

    • a NN with a single layer perceptron can only handle linear separability

    • a NN with multiple layers can learn different functions in each layer: shallow layers extract more detailed features, deeper layers extract more abstract features

  • better representation learning

    • how data is represented is important for tasks, a NN can learn a good representation of data can perform task very easy

    • a NN with multiple layers can learn different representation of data in each layer: first several layers preserve more info of input while last several layers preserve more info of output

Key Components of DL¶

  • data: input and output data used for training and testing the model.

    distribution of data in training/validation/test set

    amount of data, data augmentation

  • architecture: choice of layers, depth, width, activation, connectivity

  • objective function: measures how well the model learned

  • optimization algorithm: adjust models parameters during training to optimize the objective function.

    learning rate, number of epochs, initialization

  • regularization: Techniques used to reduce overfitting and improve generalization

  • metrics: evaluate model performance on test data

objective function¶

  • objective function $J: \mathcal{Y} \times \mathcal{Y} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$

  • objective function can be loss function plus explicit regularization term/penalty

  • loss function and penalty has many choices, the only criteriais differentiable

optimization¶

  • optimization = learning = loss minimization

  • a convex loss function can be solved by differentiation, have an analytical solution

    guaranteed to reach global minimum where derivative = 0

  • most of ML and NN problems have non-convex loss function,

    use gradient descent to reach a good-enough local minimum
